,Recommended,263360,8672378,"Posted: 11 January, 2014",all,Ribos,"This is the game I've been waiting to play, and I never even realized it until I started playing. Procedural generation... with constant renewal. Yeah, that's right, enemies keep respawning, as do boxes and missions and pretty much everything, which means there's always more stuff to do, even in the earlier portions of the game.You can craft weapons and gear. You can build the landscape (and not just in cubic meter blocks!). You can kill robots, run missions, fly ships. Do whatever. It's cool. Turning your character into a tank is as easy as going stealth assassin. My point is, if this game bores you, it's probably because of the way you're playing.Some have commented on the learning curve. Honestly, I'm not seeing it as that bad at all. Difficulty increases the further you leave the starting base, and every quest you complete gives you skill points. If ""out there"" seems too hard, just run some more lower-level quests until you're as strong as you need to be.It doesn't have the visual polish of games like Borderlands or Skyrim, but it's got a nice pre-N64 charm regardless. And besides, it's $10 for a game made by one guy. For everything you get here, complaining about the graphics is just kind of greedy."
