,Recommended,263360,23062529,"Posted: 18 May, 2016",all,Lavernius Tucker,"I've been a huge fan of this series for a long time and I decided it was time to review this entry. Not some kind of silly review (but of course there will be humor), but a full in depth look.So this game is set 10 years after the last game, 3079, but it has little to no connection with the plot of it. You're on the planet Xax and someone named the Overlord is controlling a bunch of robots all across the gigantic planet. You play as one of these robots but you're rather unique in that your model is vastly different and you're actually sentient. Go figure.A ship will drop you down to the planet in a secure area for the Red robots. The robots are divided into Red and Blue. You're on Red, so, as per usual, you have to kill Blue. The spawning area is only level 1, but as you keep exploring the difficulty will increase. Some levels might seem low but they can actually be quite difficult if you're undergeared, so be prepared. You can always head in for a brief loot trip, though.Quests are somewhat similar to 3079, but they consist of multiple objectives. You might have to disarm a bomb to get a cube or disk, or kill a robot squad, or, a little bit later into the game, vanquish a ghost from an area. You'll get credits for each objective you complete, and at the end of it, you get those delicious skill points.There's a bunch of skills, from stamina and armor, to guns and melee, to consumables and prestige. Stamina increases health, armor increases resistance, guns and melee are somewhat self explanatory, etc. You can do quests, convert areas from Blue to Red, clear out a tower (which takes a lot of time!), and kill ""X"" challenges, which are the game's form of bosses.The X challenges are located deep in high-level areas and are sometimes a higher level than the normal enemies in that area. As you kill more X challenges, different enemy types are thrown out into the wild, from rollertanks to UFOs. X challenges will usually drop a high level item or part, so if you get something like a hoverboard or grappling hook, you may have hit the jackpot.Guns are much different than 3079, instead having two main categories and three subcategories. You can get either an ammo or energy gun, and it'll be a pistol, rifle, or launcher. All guns come in three main parts that you must have to use the gun, but ammo pistols and rifles can get scopes and silencers. Gun barrels are going to have the most value of the three parts, and determine the damage, projectile speed, range, and accuracy. Magazines will determine the amount of times you can fire the gun before it needs to put ammo back in. Ammo guns draw ammo from ammo producers that you can buy from weapons stations, and don't reload. Energy guns will use your energy supply, so keep some energy consumables handy if you're mainly using an energy weapon. Gun bodies determine the shot count, any accuracy debuffs, the projectile's homing capabilities, if the rounds explode or not, and the explosion radius of the rounds.For melee, you have swords and daggers. Both can lunge with alt-fire, and have two parts; handle and blade.The handle might give you something like stun chance or corrosion, the game's form of damage over time. Swords have less of a chance for special effects but more damage, and vice versa for daggers. Daggers have lower damage but higher swing speed, swords having more power but a slower attack rate.Armor is about the same as 3079, but with something new called chips. Chips are things you can integrate into your system that boost various stats. You can reprogram chips at chip stations, rerolling their stat bonuses. They're a big help for tuning your playstyle, from a gunner with great piloting skills, to a sneaky melee fighter that has a bunch of followers.Ships are similar to 3079, but there aren't any capital ships to fight. You can get either a ship without a gun (good for getting from point A to point B quickly without any interruptions to attend to), or an armed craft. The unarmed ships require less pilot skill, but if you want to have a little firepower in the sky, you'll need a good pilot skill.There are three endings, two of which I've found. The third one has eluded me for some time. No, I won't spoil them. Figure it out yourself.Overall, it's a marvelous game for a great price. And with 5089 improving on this entry, you really can't go wrong.If you don't get it, that's okay. There's better games, but this one is still pretty good!"
