76561197998490461,Recommended,263360,9625972,"Posted: 25 March, 2014",all,cheep crybabby hatter,"I was a bit disappointed by this game. Promised to me was a procedurally generated shooter, with procedurally generated missions, weapons/equipment, NPCs, difficulty, and a world that is generated on the fly as you explore it. And, to be fair, all of these things were delivered. However, I was hoping for an exciting and dynamic experience high in variety, which is not quite what eventuated. The problem with so much procedural generation is that it makes the game a little bland.The missions are particularly so. The missions are made up of about 2-6 objectives to be completed in order, and are made up of a set list of about 8 different kinds of tasks, like ""Fight a gang of 4 robots"", ""Protect Sylvia Dee for 1:15"", or simply ""Talk to Derek"". All the missions are made up from these objectives, over and over again, just with different numbers, names, and times. These missions make little contribution to the minimal overarching story, and the content of their objectives is completely irrelevant; only whether you completed them or not.However, all of that said, despite my expectations being far higher than what was offered, I can still recommend 3089. Essentially, I was expecting 3089 to be a procedurally generated RPG, and it simply is not. It is, however, a challenging and reasonably fun shooter, with additional replay value because the world is never the same for any two characters. The missions, even there 's little incentive with respect to the story to complete them, are still fun from a gameplay perspective, and the large number of points you get to upgrade your character are a lovely bonus! Exploring the world into higher difficulty areas, to access more powerful items, is good fun too, and the world generation is actually pretty decent. I did enjoy the number of floating islands, chunky low polygon trees, impressive peaks and valleys, caverns and crags. While the missions, NPCs and weaponry all felt completely characterless, the worlds are somewhat interesting to explore.It took me a while, but eventually I started enjoying myself. If you approach it with a mind more open than mine was, I think you'll be in for a good time."
